      dek: `This is the fork in the road. Do you chase a distributor and hand them your film, or release it yourself? There's no universal right answer — but there is a right answer for <em>your</em> film, and this chapter gives you the questions that get you to it honestly.`,
      body: `<p>Every filmmaker with a finished film faces the same fork: try to sign with a distributor, or distribute it yourself. And the honest truth is that <strong>neither path is automatically better</strong> — the right choice depends on your film, your goals, and what a distributor would actually do for you. A good distributor can open doors you can't: relationships with platforms and buyers, marketing muscle, credibility, sometimes real money up front. A bad or indifferent distributor can take your rights and your revenue and then do almost nothing, leaving you worse off than if you'd released it yourself. Meanwhile, self-distribution keeps you in control and keeps more of the money, but only pays off if you're willing to do the work — the marketing, the platforms, the hustle. So the goal of this chapter isn't to sell you on DIY (even though that's what this course teaches); it's to help you make an honest decision. Let me give you the framework.</p>

<h2>What each path actually gives you</h2>

<p>Weigh the real trade-offs, not the fantasy version of either:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Traditional distribution — the upside.</b> Access to platforms and buyers you can't reach alone, marketing resources, industry credibility, and sometimes an advance. If the distributor is genuinely good and committed, this reach can dwarf what you'd manage solo.</li>
  <li><b>Traditional distribution — the cost.</b> You give up rights (often for years), a large cut of revenue, and control over how and where your film is released. And a deal is only as good as the distributor's actual effort — many take rights and do little.</li>
  <li><b>Self-distribution — the upside.</b> You keep your rights, keep a bigger share of revenue, control the strategy, and own the relationship with your audience for the next film.</li>
  <li><b>Self-distribution — the cost.</b> All the work is yours — marketing, platforms, admin — and you don't get a distributor's existing relationships or resources. It only works if you commit to the effort.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The questions that make the decision honest</h2>

<p>To choose well, get concrete and skeptical. First: <strong>is the distributor actually good, and actually interested?</strong> A real offer from a distributor with a track record of promoting films like yours is very different from a boilerplate deal from a company that will simply park your film. Ask what they'll specifically do, which platforms they'll reach, what marketing they'll fund, and talk to other filmmakers who signed with them — a distributor's reputation among filmmakers tells you more than their pitch. Second: <em>what am I actually giving up, and for how long?</em> Read the deal in terms of the distribution chain from Chapter 2 — which rights, which territories, which windows, how long the term, and how the money flows back after their cut. If you'd be signing away your film for years in exchange for vague promises and a tiny revenue share, that's a bad trade no matter how flattering the offer feels. Third: <em>am I willing and able to do the work of self-distributing?</em> DIY only pays off if you'll actually market the film, manage the platforms, and push — if you know you won't, a mediocre distributor who does <em>something</em> might beat a self-release you'll neglect. Fourth: <em>what does success look like for this film?</em> If your goal is maximum reach and a distributor can genuinely deliver it, that may be worth the cut. If your goal is keeping control, building an audience, and learning to release films you can repeat, DIY serves that better. The biggest mistake I see is filmmakers treating any distribution offer as validation and grabbing it out of relief, then regretting the terms for years. <em>An offer is not automatically a good deal.</em> The second biggest mistake is the opposite — romanticizing DIY and then not doing the work, so the film just sits on a platform unseen. Be honest with yourself about which failure mode you're prone to. Often the answer isn't purely one or the other: you might self-distribute in your home territory while licensing to a distributor abroad, or hold out for a genuinely good deal while being fully prepared to release it yourself if one doesn't come. What matters is that you decide deliberately, with the trade-offs in front of you, rather than defaulting into either path. Next, before you can weigh any deal or plan any release, you need to understand the thing you're actually negotiating over: your rights.</p>

<div class="pullquote">An offer is not automatically a good deal, and DIY is not automatically freedom. A great distributor can dwarf what you'd do alone; a bad one takes your rights and does nothing. Decide honestly — for this film.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>A director friend got a distribution offer and signed it the same week out of sheer relief that someone wanted the film. The company took worldwide rights for years, put the film on one platform with zero marketing, and it vanished. She got almost nothing and couldn't touch her own film for the length of the term. Meanwhile another friend turned down a similar weak offer, self-distributed, hustled the marketing, and reached far more people while keeping his rights. The difference wasn't luck — it was that one asked "is this actually a good deal?" and the other just heard "yes" and grabbed it.</p>
</div>`,
