      body: `<p>Here's where DIY distribution succeeds or fails: <strong>the plan.</strong> Filmmakers who self-distribute well don't wing it — they build a distribution strategy before they release, a written map that answers who the film is for, where those people are, what order to hit platforms in, what it'll cost, and what success even means. Filmmakers who self-distribute badly just push the film onto a platform and then wonder why nobody came. The difference isn't talent or luck; it's planning. And the good news is that a distribution plan isn't some mysterious document — it's a handful of clear questions answered honestly and written down so you can act on them. This chapter walks through building that plan. Everything in Module 2 that follows — choosing platforms, doing deals, running the process — plugs into the plan you build here.</p>

<h2>What a distribution plan answers</h2>

<p>Your strategy comes down to answering these, specifically, for your film:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Who is this film for?</b> Not "everyone" — the actual, describable audience. Genre fans, a community, a subject-matter niche, a festival crowd. The tighter you can name them, the easier every other decision gets.</li>
  <li><b>Where are those people already?</b> The platforms, communities, publications, and channels your audience uses. You go to where they are; you don't wait for them to find you.</li>
  <li><b>What's your goal?</b> Reach, revenue, building an audience, launching a career, festival prestige — these lead to different plans. Be honest about which one actually matters to you for this film.</li>
  <li><b>What's the sequence?</b> The order and timing of your release — festivals, then a premiere window, then VOD, then wider — your DIY version of "windows." Sequence builds momentum instead of scattering it.</li>
  <li><b>What's the budget?</b> What you can realistically spend on the release — marketing, aggregator fees, deliverables, a publicist if any. A plan you can't afford isn't a plan.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Turning answers into a release</h2>

<p>The magic of writing these down is that the answers constrain and clarify each other into an actual plan. Once you've honestly named <em>who the film is for,</em> the "where" almost answers itself — a genre horror short and a personal documentary about a specific community reach their audiences in completely different places, and knowing your audience tells you which. Once you're clear on your <em>goal,</em> you can stop chasing everything: if the goal is building an audience for your career, you might prioritize reach and email capture over squeezing out rental revenue; if the goal is recouping money, you'll weight transactional platforms and pricing differently. The <strong>sequence</strong> is where a lot of DIY releases fall apart — filmmakers dump the film everywhere at once, spending their limited attention and marketing in a single scattered burst. A planned sequence instead builds momentum: maybe a festival run creates credibility and word of mouth, then a focused premiere window concentrates attention, then VOD captures the audience that heard about it, then wider availability catches the long tail. You're orchestrating attention over time instead of blowing it all on day one. And every bit of this has to live inside your <em>budget</em> — the single most common DIY mistake is a plan that assumes resources you don't have, so be ruthless about what your release can actually afford and design around it. A modest, fully-executed plan beats an ambitious one you abandon halfway. The other thing to internalize: <strong>a distribution plan is a marketing plan.</strong> Because getting onto platforms is the easy, mechanical part, the real content of your strategy is how you'll drive the audience — which means your plan should lean heavily on the tools that do that: your press kit and EPK, your trailer, your social channels, your email list, your festival strategy, and any press you can earn. Those aren't separate from distribution; they <em>are</em> the distribution, in the sense that matters. So as you write your plan, spend most of your energy on the "how will people find out about this and be moved to watch it" question, because that's the one that actually determines whether your release works. Write the plan down, keep it realistic, sequence it for momentum, and center it on reaching real people — and you've turned "upload and hope" into an actual strategy. With the plan built, the next chapters fill in its pieces: which platforms to choose, how deals and aggregators work, and the step-by-step process of executing a release. Next up: choosing your distribution platforms.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A distribution plan is a marketing plan. Getting onto a platform is the easy part — your strategy is really about who the film is for and how you'll drive them to it. Sequence for momentum; design for the budget you actually have.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first self-release had no plan — I put the film on three platforms in one week, posted about it twice, and moved on. It sank. My next one, I wrote a one-page plan first: exactly who it was for (a specific niche audience), where they hung out online, a sequence starting with a small festival run and a focused premiere window, and a marketing budget I could actually afford. Same size film, wildly different result — because this time I was orchestrating attention instead of just making the film "available." The one-page plan was the whole difference.</p>
</div>`,
