      seoDesc: "A guide to film distribution platforms — VOD, transactional, subscription, theatrical, and physical — and how to match platforms to your film's goals. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 6 of DIY Distribution.",
      dek: `There are dozens of ways to put your film in front of people — subscription streaming, rent-or-buy, ad-supported, theatrical, physical, your own site. They're not interchangeable. Each has a different business model and reaches a different audience, and choosing well means matching the platform to your goal, not chasing the biggest name.`,
      body: `<p>Once you have a plan, you have to decide <em>where</em> the film actually lives. And here's where filmmakers get dazzled by the biggest names and forget to think. The distribution platform landscape isn't one thing — it's a set of distinct models, each with a different way of making money and a different kind of audience, and <strong>the "best" platform is simply the one that fits your film's goal.</strong> A film chasing revenue wants a different mix than one chasing reach; a niche film wants a specialist platform where its audience actually looks, not a giant general service where it drowns. So instead of asking "how do I get on the biggest streamer," the smarter question is "which platforms serve what I'm actually trying to do with this film." Let me lay out the main types so you can match them to your plan from Chapter 5.</p>

<h2>The main platform types</h2>

<p>Distribution platforms mostly fall into these buckets, each with a different model:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Transactional VOD (TVOD).</b> Viewers rent or buy your film individually. You earn per transaction. Good for revenue and for films with a motivated audience willing to pay to watch.</li>
  <li><b>Subscription VOD (SVOD).</b> Part of a service viewers pay a flat fee for. You're typically paid a license fee or a share, not per view. Big reach potential, but getting on major SVOD as an indie is hard and often routed through distributors.</li>
  <li><b>Ad-supported VOD (AVOD/FAST).</b> Free to viewers, monetized by ads; you earn a share of ad revenue based on views. Low barrier, big potential reach, lower per-viewer money — good for maximizing eyeballs.</li>
  <li><b>Theatrical &amp; screenings.</b> Cinemas, one-off screenings, four-walling, community events. Rarely a moneymaker for indies, but powerful for prestige, press, word of mouth, and a premiere moment.</li>
  <li><b>Physical &amp; your own channels.</b> Discs, and especially selling or streaming direct from your own site — where you keep the most money and own the customer relationship, but you drive all the traffic yourself.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Matching platforms to your goal</h2>

<p>The whole art of choosing platforms is fit, and it flows directly from the goal you named in your plan. If your goal is <em>revenue,</em> you'll lean toward transactional (where motivated fans pay per watch) and your own direct channels (where you keep the most), and you'll price and sequence accordingly. If your goal is <em>maximum reach,</em> ad-supported and free platforms get your film in front of the most eyeballs even though each one pays little, and that can be exactly right if you're building an audience or a reputation rather than chasing dollars. If your goal is <em>prestige and press,</em> a theatrical or festival-anchored moment matters more than any VOD placement, because it creates the story everything else hangs on. Most real releases combine several of these in a sequence — a premiere or festival moment for prestige, then transactional for the fans who'll pay, then ad-supported later for the long-tail reach — which is exactly the "windows" thinking from your plan. Two cautions from experience. First, <strong>don't chase the biggest platform for its own sake.</strong> Getting your indie onto a giant general streamer, even if you can, often means being one invisible title among tens of thousands, whereas a specialist platform serving your exact niche might deliver a far more engaged audience who actually finds and watches your film. Fit beats size. Second, being on a platform still does nothing without marketing — every platform is a place your film <em>can</em> be watched, not a guarantee it <em>will</em> be, so platform choice and your marketing plan are the same conversation. A practical note on mechanics: getting onto most of the significant VOD and streaming platforms as an independent filmmaker usually doesn't happen by you uploading directly — it happens through an aggregator or distributor who's approved to deliver to those platforms. That's the subject of the next chapter, so for now just know that "choosing platforms" and "how you get onto them" are linked: your platform choices will shape which aggregator or deal you need. Choose platforms by fit to your goal, combine them in a deliberate sequence, favor engaged audiences over raw size, and remember that placement without marketing is just a listing. Next, let's look at the deals, aggregators, and middlemen who actually get your film onto these platforms — and what they cost you.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The best platform is the one that fits your goal, not the one with the biggest name. Revenue, reach, and prestige each point to a different mix — and being on any platform does nothing without marketing to drive people there.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once spent months obsessed with getting a film onto a giant general streamer, treating it as the finish line. A mentor asked me a simple question: "And then what — how will anyone there find it?" I didn't have an answer. Meanwhile a documentary friend put her film on a small platform built around her exact subject niche, with an audience who came looking for films like hers, and it found far more of the right viewers than my big-name placement ever did. That's when I stopped chasing size and started chasing fit. The platform that matches your audience beats the platform that impresses your friends.</p>
</div>`,
