      seoDesc: "The film distribution process step by step — from deliverables and metadata to aggregator submission and going live. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 8 of DIY Distribution.",
      dek: `Enough theory — what actually happens, in order, to take your finished film to a live listing on a platform? This is the practical sequence: deliverables, metadata, artwork, submission, review, and going live. Knowing the steps means you can prepare for them instead of scrambling.`,
      body: `<p>Everything so far has been strategy. Now let's get concrete about the actual mechanical process of getting a film from "finished" to "live on a platform," because a lot of DIY stress comes from not knowing the steps and hitting them unprepared. The process is more involved than uploading a video to YouTube — platforms have exacting technical and metadata requirements, and a single missing or wrong deliverable can bounce your submission and cost you weeks. But it's also completely learnable, and once you've seen the sequence, you can prepare everything in advance so the release goes smoothly. Let me walk the steps in order.</p>

<h2>The steps, in order</h2>

<p>A typical VOD/streaming release moves through these stages:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>1. Assemble deliverables.</b> The technical package platforms require — a spec-compliant master file, closed captions/subtitles, sometimes a trailer file, audio in the right format. Each platform has its own specs; this is where most submissions get bounced.</li>
  <li><b>2. Write your metadata.</b> Title, synopsis, cast and crew, genre, ratings, keywords, release year. This is what audiences and search see — treat it as marketing, not paperwork, because it affects whether people find and click your film.</li>
  <li><b>3. Prepare artwork.</b> Poster/key art and thumbnails to each platform's dimensions. Your artwork is the single biggest driver of whether someone clicks — a weak thumbnail sinks a good film.</li>
  <li><b>4. Submit through your aggregator.</b> Deliver the package to your chosen aggregator, who checks it against platform specs and pushes it to each service. Expect to fix things they flag.</li>
  <li><b>5. Platform review &amp; QC.</b> Each platform reviews and quality-checks the film and assets before accepting. This takes time and can bounce back for corrections — build in a buffer.</li>
  <li><b>6. Go live &amp; verify.</b> The film publishes on the platform. Check every listing yourself — right title, right artwork, plays correctly, priced as intended — because errors happen and you're the one who catches them.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why preparation is the whole game</h2>

<p>The single biggest lesson of the distribution process is that <strong>almost all the pain is front-loaded into deliverables and metadata, and almost all of it is preventable.</strong> Platforms are strict about specs because they serve millions of viewers and can't accept files that don't conform — so a master that's the wrong codec, captions in the wrong format, or artwork at the wrong dimensions gets kicked back, and each bounce costs you a review cycle, which can be days or weeks. Filmmakers who go into a release without their deliverables truly ready end up in a miserable loop of submit-reject-fix-resubmit, often while a planned launch date slips away. Filmmakers who prepare the full package to spec in advance sail through. So the practical takeaway is: <em>get your deliverables and metadata genuinely ready before you start submitting,</em> ideally confirming the exact specs your aggregator and target platforms require and building the package to match. Two pieces deserve extra attention because filmmakers underrate them. First, <em>metadata is marketing, not paperwork.</em> Your synopsis, title treatment, genre tags, and keywords directly affect whether your film surfaces in search and browse and whether someone who sees it clicks — so write your synopsis like ad copy, choose genre and keywords strategically, and don't fill these fields out carelessly at 2 a.m. Second, <em>artwork does the clicking.</em> On a crowded platform, your thumbnail and poster are competing against thousands of others for a split-second decision, and a weak or amateurish image will bury even an excellent film — invest real effort (or real money) in artwork that makes people stop and click. Finally, build a time buffer into your plan: platform review and QC take longer than you expect, and things bounce, so if you have a launch date tied to marketing (a premiere, a press push, a festival), give yourself weeks of margin so a review delay doesn't blow up your carefully sequenced release. Know the steps, prepare the package to spec, treat metadata and artwork as marketing, verify every live listing yourself, and leave buffer — do that and the mechanical process stops being scary and becomes routine. That completes Module 2's craft. Module 3 is about putting all of this to work in the real world, starting with the full menu of options an indie film actually has.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Almost all the pain of distribution is front-loaded into deliverables and metadata — and almost all of it is preventable. Prepare the package to spec before you submit, treat metadata and artwork as marketing, and leave buffer for review.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first VOD submission bounced four times — wrong caption format, audio spec off, artwork the wrong dimensions, a metadata field I'd left blank. Each rejection cost me a review cycle, and my launch date, which I'd tied to a press push, slid two weeks and lost momentum. Next film, I got the exact specs up front, built every deliverable to match, wrote the metadata like ad copy, paid for a real poster, and left a three-week buffer. It went live clean on schedule. The film wasn't better — I was just prepared. In distribution, preparation is most of the job.</p>
</div>`,
