      dek: `"How do I distribute my indie film?" doesn't have one answer — it has a menu. Understanding the real range of paths available to an independent film today, and that you can combine them, is what lets you assemble a release that fits your specific film instead of forcing it into someone else's template.`,
      body: `<p>Module 3 is about putting everything together in the real world, and the right place to start is by seeing the full menu. Filmmakers often approach distribution as if there's one door to find — the distributor, or the platform — when in fact independent film distribution today is a spread of options you can mix and match. The reason this matters is that <strong>the best release for most indie films is a combination, not a single path</strong>, and you can't assemble a smart combination if you don't know what's on the menu. So let me lay out the real range of indie distribution options, so you can see them all at once and start thinking about which pieces fit your film. Everything in this course so far — rights, platforms, plans, deals — plugs into choosing among these.</p>

<h2>The real menu of indie options</h2>

<p>Here are the main paths, any of which you can combine:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Traditional distributor deal.</b> Sign your film to a distributor who handles the release for a cut and your rights. Best when you land a genuinely good, committed one (see Chapter 3).</li>
  <li><b>Sales agent + territory licensing.</b> A sales agent represents your film to buyers and licenses it territory by territory. Common for films with festival heat and international appeal.</li>
  <li><b>Aggregator-based self-distribution.</b> You keep control and use an aggregator to get onto VOD/streaming platforms yourself. The core DIY path this course centers on.</li>
  <li><b>Festival &amp; theatrical/screening route.</b> Building visibility and credibility through festivals and live screenings — often the launch phase that feeds every other option.</li>
  <li><b>Direct-to-audience.</b> Selling or streaming straight from your own site, mailing list, and community — maximum control and margin, all the traffic on you.</li>
  <li><b>Hybrid deals.</b> Combining paths — e.g., self-distribute domestically while licensing abroad, or festival-launch then aggregator VOD. Because rights are divisible, you're not locked into one.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Assembling the right combination</h2>

<p>The liberating idea here, which ties back to the rights chapter, is that these options aren't mutually exclusive — because your rights are a divisible bundle, <em>you can run several of these paths at once for different slices of your film.</em> A very common and smart indie shape looks like this: launch on the festival circuit to build credibility and word of mouth, use that momentum and any press to drive a focused VOD release through an aggregator in your home market, capture your audience directly through your own site and mailing list, and license territories abroad through a sales agent if the film has international appeal. That's four "options" from this menu working together, each handling the slice it's best at — and none of them would have been as strong alone. The key to assembling your combination is to go back to the plan from Chapter 5 and match options to your <em>goal</em> and your <em>film</em>. A festival-friendly art film leans hard on the festival/theatrical route and prestige; a genre film with a rabid niche leans on transactional VOD and direct-to-audience where those fans will pay; a film with international appeal makes room for a sales agent and territory licensing; a film whose main value is building your career and audience weights direct-to-audience and reach. There's no universal correct combination — there's the one that fits what you're trying to do with <em>this</em> film. Two honest cautions. First, <strong>more options isn't automatically better</strong> — every path you add costs attention and effort, and a focused release on two well-chosen paths usually beats a scattered attempt at six. Pick the combination you can actually execute well within your budget and energy. Second, remember that whichever options you choose, the marketing half of the chain still governs everything — festivals, VOD, direct sales, and licensing all work far better when you're actively driving audience and press to the film, so your chosen options should be wrapped in a real marketing effort, not left to fend for themselves. The menu is bigger and more flexible than most filmmakers realize, and seeing it whole is what turns "I hope someone distributes my film" into "here's the specific combination of paths I'm going to run." From here, the last three chapters zoom into particular situations and the finish line: distributing a short film, getting onto the big streamers, and pulling it all together into your own release. Next: why short films play by their own rules.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Indie distribution isn't one door to find — it's a menu you mix and match. Because your rights are divisible, you can run festivals, VOD, direct-to-audience, and licensing at once. The best release is usually a focused combination, not a single path.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>For years I thought distribution was a single choice: get the deal or don't. Then I watched a filmmaker friend run four paths at once with one film — festival launch for prestige, aggregator VOD at home for the fans, her own mailing list for direct sales, and a sales agent for a couple of foreign territories. None of those alone would have amounted to much; together they added up to a real release, because each one carried the slice it was suited for. That's when I stopped hunting for the one door and started assembling combinations. The menu was always bigger than I thought.</p>
</div>`,
