      dek: `Short films play by their own rules. They rarely make money the way features do, the platforms and audiences are different, and success looks different too. If you have a short, distributing it well means understanding what it's actually <em>for</em> — and playing to that.`,
      body: `<p>If you've got a short film, most of what's true about feature distribution needs adjusting, because <strong>shorts play a different game.</strong> Features can earn real money across VOD, streaming, and licensing; shorts almost never do — the market for paying to watch a single short is tiny. That doesn't mean distributing a short is pointless. It means the <em>goal</em> is usually different: for most filmmakers, a short is a calling card, a proof of talent, a festival contender, and a way to build audience and open doors, rather than a revenue product. Once you accept that reframe, distributing your short well becomes clear — you optimize for visibility, credibility, and connection, not for a paycheck that isn't coming. Let me lay out how shorts actually get seen.</p>

<h2>How short films get seen</h2>

<p>The realistic paths for a short, roughly in order of how most filmmakers use them:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Festivals first.</b> The festival circuit is where shorts earn their credibility, awards, and industry attention. A strong festival run is often the single most valuable thing you can do with a short — and premiere status matters, so plan it (see the Festival Strategy course).</li>
  <li><b>Curated online platforms.</b> Respected short-film platforms and channels that program and spotlight shorts can put yours in front of an audience that actually seeks shorts out — prestige placement, sometimes a modest fee.</li>
  <li><b>Your own release (YouTube/Vimeo).</b> Putting the short online yourself — usually free, for reach and audience-building. Great for a calling card; just mind the timing so you don't burn festival eligibility first.</li>
  <li><b>Bundling &amp; niche outlets.</b> Some shorts find homes in themed collections, ad-supported short channels, or subject-specific outlets where the topic or genre has a built-in audience.</li>
  <li><b>As a career tool.</b> Sending the short directly to people who matter — programmers, producers, reps, collaborators — as evidence of what you can do. Sometimes the most valuable "distribution" is a well-placed private link.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Playing the short-film game well</h2>

<p>The biggest strategic decision with a short is <strong>sequencing festivals and online release</strong>, and it's the one filmmakers most often botch. Many festivals care about premiere status and won't program a short that's already freely online, so if a festival run is part of your plan, <em>don't dump the short on YouTube the day it's finished.</em> The usual smart sequence is: do the festival circuit first (where the credibility and industry attention live), then, once the festival life has run its course, release the short online for reach and as a permanent calling card. Reverse that order and you can quietly disqualify yourself from festivals you'd have wanted. Beyond sequencing, the key is to keep your eyes on what a short is really <em>for</em>. If it's a calling card for your career, then the "distribution" that matters most may be getting it in front of the specific people who can hire you or collaborate with you — a great festival helps, but so does simply sending a strong private link to the right producer or rep, and you shouldn't overlook that direct route while chasing views. If it's about building an audience, then a well-timed public release on the platforms your audience uses, promoted properly, does more than a scattered festival run. If it's a genre or subject piece, a niche outlet or themed channel where that audience already gathers can outperform a general platform. And in all cases, <em>don't expect money</em> — go in understanding that a short's return is usually in reputation, relationships, and reach, and measure success by those, not by dollars that the short economy simply doesn't produce. One more thing worth saying plainly: a short still deserves real marketing effort within its scale. A short with a good poster, a tight synopsis, a clear sense of who it's for, and an active push behind its festival run and online release will vastly outperform an identical short that's just quietly uploaded. The chain's marketing half applies to shorts too. Distribute your short by matching the path to its true purpose, sequence festivals before a public release to protect premiere eligibility, use direct placement as a career tool, and measure success in credibility and connection rather than cash. Next, the question every filmmaker eventually asks — how do you actually get onto Netflix and the big streamers?</p>

<div class="pullquote">A short film is usually a calling card, not a revenue product. Distribute it for visibility, credibility, and connection — and sequence festivals before you put it online, or you'll quietly disqualify yourself from the festivals that matter.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I made a short early on and, out of excitement, posted it to YouTube the week it was done. Then I started researching festivals and discovered half the ones I wanted required a premiere — which I'd just thrown away for a few hundred views. My next short, I held it back, ran the festival circuit first, got into some good ones, met people who mattered, and only <em>then</em> released it publicly as a calling card. The film wasn't better; the sequence was. With shorts, when you release matters as much as where.</p>
</div>`,
