      dek: `It's the question every filmmaker asks: how do I get my film on Netflix? The honest answer is less magical than you'd hope and more useful than you'd fear. Understanding how the big streamers actually acquire films — and why they might not be the goal you think — will save you a lot of wasted effort.`,
      body: `<p>Almost every filmmaker, at some point, fixates on the same dream: my film on Netflix. So let's talk about it honestly, because the fantasy version wastes a lot of people's time. Here's the reality: <strong>the big subscription streamers do not have a public "submit your film" button, and they acquire almost nothing directly from unrepresented filmmakers.</strong> They license and buy films through established distributors, sales agents, and industry relationships — usually films that already have festival pedigree, buzz, or a track record. That doesn't mean it's impossible for an indie to end up on a major streamer, but the path runs through the industry, not through you uploading a file, and it's genuinely hard and rare for a small film. Understanding this saves you from pouring energy into a door that mostly doesn't open the way you imagine — and frees you to pursue the paths that actually work. Let me lay out the honest picture and the better alternatives.</p>

<h2>How films actually get onto the big streamers</h2>

<p>The realistic routes, none of which are "upload it yourself":</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Through a distributor or sales agent.</b> The main path — a distributor or agent with existing relationships licenses your film to the streamer. This is why a good distribution deal can be worth it for the right film.</li>
  <li><b>Off a strong festival run.</b> Major streamers watch top festivals for acquisitions. A film with real festival heat and press can attract their buyers — but that's a high bar most films don't clear.</li>
  <li><b>Via an aggregator's platform relationships.</b> Some aggregators can deliver to certain streaming services, but getting onto the flagship SVOD tiers as an unknown indie is still uncommon and not guaranteed by any aggregator's pitch.</li>
  <li><b>Not directly, as a rule.</b> The big SVOD services don't take open submissions from individual filmmakers. Anyone promising guaranteed placement for a fee deserves deep skepticism.</li>
  <li><b>The alternative streamers that DO take indies.</b> Ad-supported and transactional platforms, and many smaller/niche streaming services, are far more accessible via aggregators — and often better for actually being seen.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why the big streamer may not be the goal</h2>

<p>Here's the reframe that matters most, and it echoes Chapter 6: <strong>getting onto a giant streamer, even if you could, is often not the win it appears to be.</strong> On a service with tens of thousands of titles and an algorithm optimized for its own big originals, a small acquired indie can land, get almost no promotion, and vanish into the catalog unseen — "on Netflix" and "watched on Netflix" are very different outcomes, and the first without the second does little for you. Meanwhile the platforms that <em>do</em> readily take indie films — transactional VOD, ad-supported services, and niche streamers — are frequently better for actually reaching an audience, because on a transactional or niche platform your marketing can drive motivated viewers straight to a purchase or a watch, whereas on a giant SVOD you're at the mercy of their promotion. So rather than chasing the prestige of a big-streamer logo, the smarter play for most indie films is to pursue the accessible platforms where your own marketing can move the needle, and to let a major-streamer placement be a bonus that <em>might</em> come off a strong festival run or a good distributor — not the plan you stake everything on. Two practical warnings. First, <strong>be extremely skeptical of anyone who promises to get your film on Netflix (or any major streamer) for a fee.</strong> The big services don't work that way, and "guaranteed placement" pitches are a classic way indie filmmakers get separated from their money — a legitimate aggregator will tell you honestly which platforms they can and can't reliably deliver to. Second, if getting onto a major streamer genuinely is your goal, the real levers are the ones this course has covered: make a film strong enough to earn a festival run, build the pedigree and press that attracts buyers, and get a good distributor or sales agent who has the relationships — there's no shortcut around that. But for most filmmakers, the honest and liberating conclusion is that <em>the big streamer isn't the finish line it's cracked up to be,</em> and the accessible platforms plus your own marketing will get your film in front of more of the right people than a logo you can't leverage. Let the dream go a little, and you'll distribute smarter. That clears the ground for the final chapter, where we pull the whole course together into running your own release.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The big streamers have no "submit your film" button — they acquire through distributors, agents, and festival heat. And "on Netflix" isn't "watched on Netflix." For most indies, accessible platforms plus your own marketing beat a logo you can't leverage.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I burned a solid year fixated on getting a film onto a major streamer — chasing contacts, entertaining a "we can get you on for a fee" pitch I thankfully walked away from, treating it as the only real success. Nothing came of it. A filmmaker I know skipped that whole fantasy, put her film on transactional and niche platforms an aggregator could actually reach, and marketed the hell out of it to her audience. She reached far more of the right viewers than my imaginary Netflix slot ever would have. The logo was never the point. Being watched was.</p>
</div>`,
