      dek: `This is where it all comes together. You understand the chain, your rights, your platforms, your deals, and your options — now you run the actual release. A self-distributed launch is a project you manage, start to finish, and doing it deliberately is what turns a finished film into a film that's genuinely seen.`,
      body: `<p>Everything in this course has been building to this: actually running your own release. Independent film distribution, done yourself, is a project — one you plan, launch, and manage over time, drawing on everything you've learned about the chain, rights, platforms, deals, and options. It's not a single button you press; it's a coordinated push that puts your film in front of an audience and keeps pushing until it's genuinely seen. The filmmakers who do this well aren't necessarily the ones with the best films or the biggest budgets — they're the ones who <strong>treat the release with the same seriousness and commitment they gave the production.</strong> You spent months or years making the film; the release deserves real, sustained effort too, not a tired afterthought. Let me pull the whole course together into how a self-distributed release actually runs.</p>

<h2>Running the release, start to finish</h2>

<p>A self-distributed launch, drawing on everything so far:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Lock your plan and rights.</b> Confirm your audience, goal, platform mix, and sequence (Ch. 5), and know exactly which rights you hold and are using (Ch. 4). This is your map.</li>
  <li><b>Prepare everything to spec.</b> Deliverables, metadata, artwork, and your marketing assets — EPK, trailer, stills — genuinely ready before launch (Ch. 8). Preparation prevents most disasters.</li>
  <li><b>Build momentum first.</b> Where it fits, launch through festivals and press to create credibility and word of mouth before the wide release (Ch. 9), so you're not releasing into silence.</li>
  <li><b>Go live in sequence.</b> Release across your chosen platforms in your planned order through your aggregator (Ch. 6–8), concentrating attention rather than scattering it.</li>
  <li><b>Market relentlessly.</b> Drive the audience the whole time — social, email, press, community, your festival run — because placement without marketing is invisible. This is the real work.</li>
  <li><b>Track, adjust, and keep going.</b> Watch what's working, fix what isn't, keep the film alive with ongoing pushes, and capture your audience for the next film. A release is a campaign, not a day.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making it real — and what you carry forward</h2>

<p>The single most important thing I can tell you about running your own release is that <strong>it's a campaign, not an event.</strong> The failure mode of DIY distribution is treating "the film went live" as the finish line — you push hard for launch day, then go quiet, and the film fades. The success mode is treating launch as the <em>start</em> of a sustained effort: you keep marketing, keep finding new pockets of audience, keep leveraging every festival, review, and bit of press, and keep the film in front of people for weeks and months, not hours. That relentless, ongoing drive is what separates films that get seen from films that were technically available. And it circles back to the very first chapter's theme: <em>you are not powerless here.</em> Nobody is coming to save your film — but you don't need them to, because you now understand the whole machine and can run it yourself. Two closing pieces of wisdom. First, <strong>capture your audience.</strong> Every viewer who finds this film is a potential viewer for your next one, so build your email list and your community as you go, because the most valuable long-term asset of a self-distributed release isn't this film's revenue — it's the audience relationship you build, which compounds across a career. The filmmakers who thrive over time are the ones who turn each release into a growing audience rather than a one-off. Second, <em>be kind to yourself about outcomes.</em> A great DIY release still might not make much money or reach millions — the indie landscape is hard, and success is often measured in a real audience found, relationships built, an audience captured, and lessons learned that make the next release better, rather than in a jackpot. Judge your release by whether you did the work well and got the film genuinely in front of the right people, not by a fantasy of overnight success. If you plan deliberately, prepare thoroughly, sequence for momentum, market relentlessly, capture your audience, and keep going past launch day, you'll have done exactly what DIY distribution is for: taken a finished film and gotten it seen, on your own terms, while building something that lasts. That's the whole course. You now know how film distribution works, when to self-distribute, how to handle rights, platforms, deals, and options, and how to run a release from start to finish. You've finished the course — now go get your film in front of an audience.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A self-distributed release is a campaign, not an event. Launch day is the start, not the finish. Market relentlessly, capture your audience, and keep going — because nobody's coming to save your film, and you no longer need them to.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My best release wasn't my best film — it was the one I refused to let die after launch day. I'd learned my lesson from earlier films that I pushed for a week and abandoned. This time I treated the release like the production: a real project with sustained effort. I kept marketing for months, worked every festival and review, built my email list the whole way, and kept finding new corners of audience. It reached far more people than my "better" films that I'd let fade. And the email list I built carried straight into the next film. The release was where the work paid off.</p>
</div>`,
